32
00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:09.741
There is a big discovery in science, and it's that

33
00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:13.780
most ovarian cancers don't actually start in the ovary.

34
00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:15.740
They start in the fallopian tube.

35
00:02:16.109 --> 00:02:19.620
And I was like, "What?" So ovarian cancer is not ovarian cancer, it's fallopian

36
00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:20.240
tube cancer.

37
00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:23.460
In this slide is the proof of this discovery.

38
00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:26.680
See, this is what healthy fallopian tube cells look like.

39
00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:30.960
But scientists found these precancerous cells, the

40
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.160
beginning of most ovarian cancers.

41
00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:36.200
This is not an easy disease. It is brutal.

42
00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:40.060
The surgeries, the chemo treatments, it is just terrible.

43
00:02:40.540 --> 00:02:44.420
The reason this is such a big deal is because if you're trying to prevent

44
00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:47.160
cancer, you have to be looking in the right place.

45
00:02:47.900 --> 00:02:51.109
Which is why this discovery is leading to the first breakthroughs we've

46
00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:52.740
seen in decades.

47
00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:57.300
We see it so clearly every single day in the people we take care

48
00:02:57.380 --> 00:03:00.780
of. It's impossible not to want to drop everything and work on it.

49
00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:09.440
But that's really what we need to do if we are

50
00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:12.860
going to close what is a very large implementation

51
00:03:12.980 --> 00:03:16.680
gap between this scientific breakthrough and making

52
00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:20.180
life-saving prevention an opportunity for all people,

53
00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:23.500
and that's what I'm going to talk to you briefly about today.

54
00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:28.920
So the graph on the right was published in "The Wall Street Journal"

55
00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:33.140
25 years ago, and it cast ovarian cancer

56
00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:36.660
as a disheartening outlier in the world's otherwise

57
00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:39.220
encouraging progress against cancer.

58
00:03:40.380 --> 00:03:43.680
In the years leading up to this article, three pivotal

59
00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:47.100
developments made it possible to bend the arc toward

60
00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:48.900
eliminating this disease.

61
00:03:50.180 --> 00:03:53.860
The 1993 federal mandate requiring the inclusion of

62
00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:56.860
women in publicly funded research in the US,

63
00:03:57.940 --> 00:04:01.840
the cloning of the BRCA genes, and recognition of hereditary

64
00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:02.910
ovarian cancer,

65
00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:07.690
and the first observations of serous tubal intraepithelial

66
00:04:07.760 --> 00:04:11.520
carcinoma, or STIC, the immediate precursor to high-grade

67
00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:15.020
serous ovarian cancer in the fallopian tube.

68
00:04:16.940 --> 00:04:20.921
Also in 2000, medical students like me were taught that

69
00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:24.390
most ovarian cancers come from ovarian surface

70
00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:28.240
epithelium, and many are still taught this today.

71
00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:32.500
But we now know that less than 20% of what we have

72
00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:36.100
long called ovarian cancer is actually ovarian cancer,

73
00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:40.360
and you can see that in the bottom left in the teal boxes.

74
00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:44.860
The rest, either directly or indirectly, comes from the

75
00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:45.860
fallopian tube.

76
00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:51.560
Now, the longstanding belief that ovarian cancer arises from the

77
00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:55.160
ovarian surface epithelium really established

78
00:04:55.300 --> 00:04:59.220
ovarian removal as the dominant risk-reducing strategy for

79
00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:03.300
high-risk women with pathogenic variants like BRCA at the turn

80
00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:04.080
of the century.

81
00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:08.620
The fallopian tubes, though, are always removed alongside the ovaries for

82
00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:12.520
practical reasons, but at the time, back then, were regarded

83
00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:15.780
as a bystander organ of minimal significance.

84
00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:20.600
As of today, there's still no standard prevention strategy for

85
00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:22.480
average and moderate risk women.

86
00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:27.050
And for high-risk women, oophorectomy is still recommended as

87
00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:30.460
early as 35, triggering immediate

88
00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:34.480
menopause with well-documented detriment to quality of life

89
00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:37.700
and emerging long-term health consequences.

90
00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:43.060
As a result, women with germline pathogenic variants in genes

91
00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:46.910
like BRCA are increasingly delaying surgery beyond the

92
00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:49.520
recommended age. And you can see these recent data.

93
00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:53.960
About 56% of women who have a BRCA1 pathogenic variant

94
00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:56.680
delay risk-reducing surgery beyond the age of 40.

95
00:05:57.180 --> 00:06:01.120
And about a third of women with BRCA2 pathogenic variants

96
00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:03.520
wait until after the age of 45.

97
00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:08.120
And this is worrisome because we know the risk of STIC and high-grade

98
00:06:08.180 --> 00:06:12.160
serous cancer rises with each passing year, and you can see that in the

99
00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:15.884
bottom left.Just as important though,

100
00:06:16.124 --> 00:06:19.844
a diagnosis of STIC or pre-cancer, how we currently

101
00:06:19.884 --> 00:06:23.084
understand it, is not necessarily benign.

102
00:06:23.604 --> 00:06:27.384
And these are data from Miranda Steenbeck and colleagues here on

103
00:06:27.444 --> 00:06:31.414
the right which suggests that if STIC is already present in

104
00:06:31.444 --> 00:06:34.744
the fallopian tube at the time of risk-reducing surgery

105
00:06:35.284 --> 00:06:39.234
the threat of future high-grade serous peritoneal cancer is

106
00:06:39.344 --> 00:06:43.204
still considerable, upwards of 30% at 10

107
00:06:43.244 --> 00:06:43.684
years.

108
00:06:44.524 --> 00:06:47.984
In other words, as currently practiced, surgical

109
00:06:48.004 --> 00:06:51.914
prophylaxis misses the mark on prevention and interception.

110
00:06:53.444 --> 00:06:57.424
What if we could offer high-risk women the intervention they need the most,

111
00:06:57.644 --> 00:07:01.284
a salpingectomy, at a younger age and safely delay the

112
00:07:01.404 --> 00:07:05.084
oophorectomy bit until closer to the natural age of menopause?

113
00:07:05.684 --> 00:07:09.464
And that's the idea behind the international TUBAWISP-2

114
00:07:09.584 --> 00:07:11.524
trial, which is actively enrolling.

115
00:07:12.044 --> 00:07:15.704
And this is a preference trial that compares quality of life and

116
00:07:15.864 --> 00:07:18.764
oncologic equivalence between risk reducing

117
00:07:18.944 --> 00:07:22.284
salpingo-oophorectomy, the standard of care, versus

118
00:07:22.524 --> 00:07:26.214
salpingectomy followed by delayed oophorectomy closer to the

119
00:07:26.264 --> 00:07:29.424
natural age of menopause in high-risk women.

120
00:07:31.264 --> 00:07:35.054
But only focusing prevention on high-risk women will

121
00:07:35.144 --> 00:07:36.704
only get us so far.

122
00:07:37.524 --> 00:07:40.754
Germline pathogenic variants are rare with a carrier

123
00:07:40.884 --> 00:07:44.664
frequency collectively less than 2% and many

124
00:07:44.744 --> 00:07:48.234
carriers lack family history needed to prompt genetic

125
00:07:48.284 --> 00:07:48.884
testing.

126
00:07:49.784 --> 00:07:53.624
We know many unfortunately first undergo genetic testing only

127
00:07:53.744 --> 00:07:57.604
after their first cancer diagnosis, and this is a huge failure in

128
00:07:57.684 --> 00:08:01.564
prevention and Marie Lasker called this out decades ago.

129
00:08:03.244 --> 00:08:06.904
On the right, I'm showing you that 80% of women with ovarian

130
00:08:06.964 --> 00:08:10.564
cancer actually have no identifiable predisposition.

131
00:08:10.604 --> 00:08:13.994
We can't identify them. They're seemingly average risk.

132
00:08:15.624 --> 00:08:19.464
And despite decades of trying, screening has proved

133
00:08:19.524 --> 00:08:23.343
categorically ineffective. You can see here the long-term follow-up results from

134
00:08:23.364 --> 00:08:27.244
the UKCTOCS trial, the largest ovarian cancer screening trial in the

135
00:08:27.304 --> 00:08:30.884
history of time, and there was no difference in mortality between

136
00:08:30.984 --> 00:08:32.884
screening and no screening groups.

137
00:08:34.024 --> 00:08:37.865
And we often define therapeutic success by

138
00:08:37.944 --> 00:08:41.304
incremental gains like months longer in remission.

139
00:08:41.744 --> 00:08:45.504
Here on the right, 12 months remission with a five-drug

140
00:08:45.624 --> 00:08:49.484
regimen versus 17.5 months with standard

141
00:08:49.544 --> 00:08:50.044
treatment.

142
00:08:50.954 --> 00:08:54.884
And so when you consider this sobering reality,

143
00:08:54.944 --> 00:08:58.824
the observation that bilateral salpingectomy, removing both

144
00:08:58.844 --> 00:09:02.174
fallopian tubes, reduces the risk of ovarian cancer in the general

145
00:09:02.264 --> 00:09:05.764
population by at least 50% is pretty

146
00:09:05.824 --> 00:09:06.494
mind-blowing.

147
00:09:07.754 --> 00:09:11.464
This observation inspired what is known as opportunistic

148
00:09:11.524 --> 00:09:15.464
salpingectomy, which is specifically the removal of the

149
00:09:15.564 --> 00:09:19.404
post-reproductive fallopian tubes to decrease the risk of serous

150
00:09:19.544 --> 00:09:23.444
ovarian cancer at the time of other abdominal surgeries

151
00:09:23.484 --> 00:09:27.284
when the patient is there already in the operating room for some other

152
00:09:27.344 --> 00:09:31.244
reason, incurring the risk of that primary surgery, having anesthesia,

153
00:09:32.204 --> 00:09:36.004
most commonly a hysterectomy or a woman who chooses permanent

154
00:09:36.084 --> 00:09:39.874
contraception and is going in for a tubal ligation,

155
00:09:40.324 --> 00:09:44.224
but could be for the hundreds of thousands of other abdominal surgeries

156
00:09:44.284 --> 00:09:46.524
that women have in this country every year.

157
00:09:47.934 --> 00:09:51.504
And the most compelling population level effectiveness data for

158
00:09:51.564 --> 00:09:54.984
opportunistic salpingectomy, really the only data so far,

159
00:09:55.564 --> 00:09:59.224
have been maturing in BC, Canada since the launch of the province-wide

160
00:09:59.344 --> 00:10:03.224
OVCARE initiative in 2010 under the leadership of Diane

161
00:10:03.264 --> 00:10:05.584
Miller and David Huntsman, Jillian Hanley.

162
00:10:06.444 --> 00:10:09.984
And by 2020 in BC, salpingectomy had largely

163
00:10:10.024 --> 00:10:13.924
replaced tubal ligation and was added to 75% to

164
00:10:14.024 --> 00:10:17.964
80% of hysterectomies, and you can see that in the small graphs there.

165
00:10:19.224 --> 00:10:22.804
Last month, Jillian Hanley publicly announced the hazard

166
00:10:22.864 --> 00:10:26.664
ratio for salpingectomy at SGO, an astounding

167
00:10:26.824 --> 00:10:27.934
0.22,

168
00:10:28.784 --> 00:10:32.484
evidence that opportunistic salpingectomy reduces the risk of

169
00:10:32.524 --> 00:10:35.804
serous ovarian cancer by nearly 80%.

170
00:10:36.564 --> 00:10:40.434
And this is the type of statistic that drives inflection points in

171
00:10:40.464 --> 00:10:42.004
medicine and public health.

172
00:10:43.844 --> 00:10:47.724
In the US, more than a million women choose permanent

173
00:10:47.764 --> 00:10:51.244
contraception by way of tubal ligation annually, and

174
00:10:51.404 --> 00:10:55.204
hundreds undergo hysterectomy or other post-reproductive abdominal

175
00:10:55.224 --> 00:10:59.204
surgeries, and these represent substantial implementation

176
00:10:59.224 --> 00:11:02.924
windows for integrating opportunistic salpingectomy into routine

177
00:11:03.024 --> 00:11:04.264
care in our country.

178
00:11:05.644 --> 00:11:09.384
However, the status quo of adoption in the US has been really

179
00:11:09.444 --> 00:11:12.784
disheartening. Claims data suggests that adoption of

180
00:11:12.884 --> 00:11:16.584
opportunistic salpingectomy at the time of inpatient hysterectomy has

181
00:11:16.684 --> 00:11:20.024
stalled out at around 60% since 2018.

182
00:11:20.584 --> 00:11:24.264
We have no idea what adoption trends are at the more common outpatient

183
00:11:24.324 --> 00:11:27.884
hysterectomy because of the way claims data are in the United

184
00:11:28.004 --> 00:11:28.404
States.

185
00:11:29.644 --> 00:11:33.424
And data also reveals striking gaps in uptake for permanent

186
00:11:33.464 --> 00:11:36.564
contraception, and you can see that there on the right.

187
00:11:36.584 --> 00:11:40.384
Non-Hispanic White women are more likely to have a salpingectomy in our

188
00:11:40.424 --> 00:11:43.064
country than any other racial or ethnic group.

189
00:11:44.704 --> 00:11:48.684
And then the greatest implementation gap is arguably the most infuriating,

190
00:11:49.224 --> 00:11:53.124
salpingectomy as an alternative to tubal ligation at the time a woman

191
00:11:53.224 --> 00:11:56.524
has her last baby. This is the most common and

192
00:11:56.624 --> 00:11:59.744
cost-effective episode of care for opportunistic

193
00:11:59.844 --> 00:12:03.744
salpingectomy. Yet it is precisely in this setting, as you

194
00:12:03.764 --> 00:12:07.084
can see there on the left, that adoption remains the

195
00:12:07.244 --> 00:12:11.024
lowest, around 11% to 14%. And

196
00:12:11.064 --> 00:12:14.584
in both of these cases of index and interval permanent

197
00:12:14.624 --> 00:12:18.014
contraception, Black race and Medicaid insurance are

198
00:12:18.044 --> 00:12:20.114
associated with a lower likelihood of

199
00:12:20.124 --> 00:12:24.108
salpingectomy.And so these disparities force

200
00:12:24.168 --> 00:12:27.408
us to confront a difficult truth in our country.

201
00:12:27.418 --> 00:12:31.388
The implementation gap is less and less about lack of knowledge,

202
00:12:32.038 --> 00:12:35.508
but more about our lack of action to care about these

203
00:12:35.568 --> 00:12:39.468
statistics enough to address the germane awareness

204
00:12:39.508 --> 00:12:42.348
and access barriers embedded in our healthcare system.

205
00:12:43.628 --> 00:12:47.228
There are loads of recommendations to support action.

206
00:12:47.568 --> 00:12:50.968
We've had them in the US for over a decade, along with growing

207
00:12:51.168 --> 00:12:54.948
global consensus that opportunistic salpingectomy is an important

208
00:12:55.388 --> 00:12:59.168
cancer risk-reducing strategy for average-risk women who've

209
00:12:59.208 --> 00:13:03.128
completed their families and are already undergoing some other abdominal or

210
00:13:03.188 --> 00:13:04.048
pelvic surgery.

211
00:13:04.968 --> 00:13:08.868
And so I'll just take a moment now. We'll briefly consider what are these

212
00:13:08.908 --> 00:13:12.728
barriers that really separate us from these recommendations and

213
00:13:12.768 --> 00:13:14.877
universal reach of prevention?

214
00:13:16.208 --> 00:13:19.728
Well, as probably most of you know, coding and health plan

215
00:13:19.888 --> 00:13:23.288
coverage are bedrock access barriers, and our

216
00:13:23.308 --> 00:13:27.268
existing procedure codes, the ones I use every day, are

217
00:13:27.348 --> 00:13:31.288
ambiguous and disincentivizing, and they're not fit for purpose.

218
00:13:31.908 --> 00:13:35.848
Health plans don't consistently include newer coverage

219
00:13:35.988 --> 00:13:39.808
language for salpingectomy as a preferred alternative to

220
00:13:39.848 --> 00:13:40.698
tubal ligation,

221
00:13:41.548 --> 00:13:45.388
or wording that is inclusive of opportunistic salpingectomy as

222
00:13:45.428 --> 00:13:48.888
an add-on procedure at non-GYN abdominal

223
00:13:49.028 --> 00:13:49.607
surgery.

224
00:13:50.728 --> 00:13:54.068
And beyond that, private health plans commonly impose

225
00:13:54.168 --> 00:13:58.048
cost-sharing that is contrary to ACA requirements for preventive

226
00:13:58.168 --> 00:14:01.788
services. And this is really apparent in

227
00:14:02.288 --> 00:14:06.138
intakes from the National Women's Law Center CoverHer Hotline, and we recently

228
00:14:06.148 --> 00:14:09.088
reviewed six months' worth of these from last

229
00:14:09.148 --> 00:14:12.868
year. And you can see that the vast

230
00:14:12.908 --> 00:14:16.528
majority of intakes here are related to lack of

